<!-- Guidelines: https://docs.spacestation14.io/en/getting-started/pr-guideline -->

## About the PR
I made moths take less _extra_ damage from being on-fire (_not_ to be confused with their base heat weakness) to give them time to react, and to make it more fair for them compared to everyone else.
This should give moths roughly twice the time to react upon being set on fire.

## Why / Balance
This has been changed due to moths having an extremely easily abused weakness to flames; any raider or traitor could pick bartender, grab a bottle or two of alcohol, and set fire to every moth they see, killing them within *5s*, with little they could do about it once they realised what was happening.

This also posed an unfair disadvantage to combat roles, as even a moth HoS or Captain could be *very* easily killed with just 20u of napalm, made with easily acquired materials at no cost.

## Technical details
I just changed;
  - type: Flammable
    damage:
      types:
        Heat: 4.5 # moths burn more easily
        
to;

  - type: Flammable
    damage:
      types:
        Heat: 2 # moths burn more easily
        
## Media
Unchanged, upstream example;

https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/2fb1c589-7db7-4f92-bd29-674224fdab0e

New, PR example; (please note I accidentally gave the human urist an extra spray)

### Describe the bug

I ran into an issue with a helper in a view component I'm trying to render in LookBook.

Inside a VC I'm using this format [`helpers.svg`](https://github.com/avo-hq/avo/pull/3632/files#diff-76d4c03eb15d4344cb7307670c8bdb29db18497047c139db9fc29882971d30eaR72) to call an [`svg`](https://github.com/avo-hq/avo/blob/main/app/helpers/avo/application_helper.rb#L63) method I have in a Rails helper module.

I'm getting this error which is probably because you're running it in an isolated context somewhere.

We use the `helpers.` pattern everywhere and before we go and refactor everything, maybe there's something that can fix it for us.

issue.title: fix: handle locals() calls in wrapped modules by static analysis
issue.body:
## Summary

This PR fixes bundling of modules that use `locals()` to dynamically access imported symbols, a pattern used by libraries like httpx to set `__module__` attributes.

## Changes

- **Static analysis for `locals()` calls**: When a module-level `locals()` call is detected, it's replaced with a statically determined dictionary containing all module-level symbols
- **`__all__` reference detection**: Added detection for when `__all__` variable is referenced elsewhere in the module (e.g., in loops), ensuring it's preserved when needed
- **AST builder enhancement**: Added `dict()` and `dict_item()` helper functions to the ast_builder for cleaner dictionary construction
- **Test fixture**: Added test case based on httpx's pattern of using `locals()` to access imported symbols

## Problem & Solution

The issue occurred when bundling modules that use this pattern:
```python
from ._internal import MyClass, my_func
__all__ = ["MyClass", "my_func"]
__locals = locals()  # Capture module-level locals
for __name in __all__:
    setattr(__locals[__name], "__module__", "mypkg")
```

In the bundled wrapper function, `locals()` returns function-local variables, not the imported symbols which are now global. The solution uses static analysis to determine what `locals()` would return at module level and replaces it with a dictionary literal containing the correct symbols.

## Test Results

-  All existing tests pass
-  New test fixture for the httpx pattern works correctly
-  Clippy validation passes (only unused `dict_item` warning, kept for future use)

  - Wrapper modules now initialize once, are ordered by dependencies, and wire imports immediately during wrapper init.
